7    76.799074     3.452593  \n\n===== Missing Value Count per Column =====\ndt                                              0\nLandAverageTemperature                         12\nLandAverageTemperatureUncertainty              12\nLandMaxTemperature                           1200\nLandMaxTemperatureUncertainty                1200\nLandMinTemperature                           1200\nLandMinTemperatureUncertainty                1200\nLandAndOceanAverageTemperature               1200\nLandAndOceanAverageTemperatureUncertainty    1200\nYear                                            0\nMonth                                           0\ndtype: int64\n\nCount of extreme temperature months (|Z-score|>2): 100\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":1},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Viz 1: Global Land vs Land+Ocean Temperature Trend (1850–2015)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))\nplt.plot(year_df['Year'], year_df['LandAverageTemperature'], color='#c82423', lw=1.5, label='Global Average Land Temperature')\nplt.plot(year_df['Year'], year_df['LandAndOceanAverageTemperature'], color='#1f77b4', lw=1.5, label='Land And Ocean Average Temperature')\nplt.axvline(x=1950, linestyle='--', color='gray', label='Rapid Warming Starting Point: 1950')\nplt.title(\"Global Temperature Trends from 1850 to 2015\", fontsize=14)\nplt.xlabel(\"Year\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Average Temperature (°C)\")\nplt.legend()\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-25T03:01:45.384501Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-25T03:01:45.384818Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-25T03:01:45.693755Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-25T03:01:45.384788Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-25T03:01:45.692837Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1400x600 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":2},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"This dual line chart compares annual average land-only temperature and combined land+ocean global temperature from 1850 to 2015. A vertical dashed reference line marks 1950, the starting point of accelerated anthropogenic warming identified.\n### Key Findings\n1. Both land and combined global temperatures show a consistent upward trend across the full time series.\n2. Land surface temperature rises faster than land-ocean blended temperature, confirming amplified continental warming.\n3. Warming velocity clearly accelerates after 1950, with the steepest upward slope occurring after 1980.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Viz 2: Land & Ocean Temp with 10-Year Rolling Mean + 95% Uncertainty Band\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))\n# Raw yearly average\nplt.plot(year_df['Year'], year_df['LandAndOceanAverageTemperature'], color='#d62728', lw=2, label='Yearly Average')\n# 10-year rolling mean\nyear_df['Roll10_Mean'] = year_df['LandAndOceanAverageTemperature'].rolling(window=10).mean()\nplt.plot(year_df['Year'], year_df['Roll10_Mean'], color='black', lw=2, linestyle='--', label='10-Year Rolling Mean')\n# 95% confidence uncertainty fill\nplt.fill_between(\n    year_df['Year'],\n    year_df['LandAndOceanAverageTemperature'] - year_df['LandAndOceanAverageTemperatureUncertainty'],\n    year_df['LandAndOceanAverageTemperature'] + year_df['LandAndOceanAverageTemperatureUncertainty'],\n    color='#ffbaba', alpha=0.5, label='Uncertainty (95% CI)'\n)\nplt.title(\"Global Land & Ocean Average Temperature (1850-Present)\", fontsize=14)\nplt.xlabel(\"Year\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Temperature (°C)\")\nplt.legend()\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-25T03:01:59.655036Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-25T03:01:59.655409Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-25T03:01:59.913903Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-25T03:01:59.655379Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-25T03:01:59.912899Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1200x600 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":3},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Red solid line = raw yearly average global land+ocean temperature; black dashed line = 10-year rolling moving average to eliminate short-term climate noise. Semi-transparent pink shaded area represents the 95% confidence interval of measurement uncertainty from historical weather stations.\n### Key Findings\n1. Short-term annual temperature fluctuations are substantial, while the 10-year rolling mean isolates the unambiguous long-term warming signal.\n2. Historical measurement uncertainty (shaded width) is much larger in the 1850–1900 period due to sparse observation networks, and narrows significantly after 1950 with global instrument standardization.\n3. The smoothed trend shows near-linear warming after 1960 with no natural cooling reversal.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Viz 3: Land Max vs Min Temperature (5-Year Rolling Average)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))\nyear_df['Roll5_Max'] = year_df['LandMaxTemperature'].rolling(5).mean()\nyear_df['Roll5_Min'] = year_df['LandMinTemperature'].rolling(5).mean()\nplt.plot(year_df['Year'], year_df['Roll5_Max'], color='crimson', lw=2, label='Max Temperature (5-yr MA)')\nplt.plot(year_df['Year'], year_df['Roll5_Min'], color='navy', lw=2, label='Min Temperature (5-yr MA)')\nplt.title(\"Land Max vs Min Temperatures (5-Year Rolling Mean)\", fontsize=14)\nplt.xlabel(\"Year\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Temperature (°C)\")\nplt.legend()\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-25T03:02:13.025958Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-25T03:02:13.026875Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-25T03:02:13.252998Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-25T03:02:13.026844Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-25T03:02:13.252141Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1200x600 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":4},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Crimson line: 5-year rolling average of annual global maximum land temperature; navy blue line: 5-year rolling average of annual global minimum land temperature. The 5-year window filters interannual noise to reveal long-term thermal range shifts.\n### Key Findings\n1. Both daily maximum and minimum land temperatures exhibit clear upward trends over 165 years.\n2. Nighttime minimum temperatures warm significantly faster than daytime maximum temperatures, compressing the diurnal temperature range (DTR).\n3. The gap between max and min temperature shrinks continuously after 1950, a well-documented signature of anthropogenic climate change.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Viz 4: Climate Warming Stripes (Temperature Anomaly Heatmap Stripes)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(16, 4), dpi=200)\nax = plt.gca()\nanomaly_vals = year_df[\"Temp_Anomaly\"].values.reshape(1, -1)\nnorm = TwoSlopeNorm(vmin=anomaly_vals.min(), vcenter=0, vmax=anomaly_vals.max())\ncmap = plt.get_cmap(\"RdBu_r\")\nax.imshow(anomaly_vals, cmap=cmap, norm=norm, aspect='auto', extent=[year_df[\"Year\"].min(), year_df[\"Year\"].max(), 0, 1])\nax.set_xlabel(\"Year\", fontsize=11)\nax.set_title(\"Global Warming Stripes (Temperature Anomalies from 1850)\", fontsize=16, pad=18)\nax.set_yticks([])\nplt.xticks([1860, 1880, 1900, 1920, 1940, 1960, 1980, 2000], fontsize=12)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-25T03:02:25.191383Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-25T03:02:25.191729Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-25T03:02:25.618062Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-25T03:02:25.1917Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-25T03:02:25.617191Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 3200x800 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":5},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The iconic climate stripe visualization designed by Ed Hawkins. Each vertical stripe represents one calendar year. Color gradient: blue = cooler-than-average annual temperature, red = warmer-than-average annual temperature, centered on the 1850–2015 global mean baseline.\n### Key Findings\n1. All early industrial years (1850–1940) are dominated by cool blue tones, indicating below-average global temperatures.\n2. A gradual color shift to pale orange begins after 1950, accelerating to deep saturated red from 1980 onward.\n3. The rightmost decades (2000–2015) show the hottest consistent anomalies, visually communicating unprecedented modern warming without complex axes.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Viz 5: Monthly Temperature Anomaly Distribution by Decade (Boxplot)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))\n# Add hue=\"Decade\" + legend=False to resolve palette deprecation warning\nsns.boxplot(data=df_recent, x=\"Decade\", y=\"Monthly_Anomaly\", hue=\"Decade\", palette=\"RdBu_r\", legend=False)\nplt.axhline(y=0, linestyle='--', color='black')\nplt.title(\"Distribution of Monthly Temperature Anomalies by Decade\", fontsize=14)\nplt.xlabel(\"Decade\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Temperature Anomaly (°C)\")\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-25T03:02:40.099217Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-25T03:02:40.100274Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-25T03:02:40.547726Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-25T03:02:40.100236Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-25T03:02:40.546867Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1400x600 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":6},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Boxplot grouping all monthly temperature anomalies by decade, baseline = 1951–1980 seasonal average. Horizontal black dashed line marks zero anomaly (climate reference point). Box edges = 25th/75th percentiles; whiskers = full data range; dots = outlier extreme monthly temperatures.\n### Key Findings\n1. All decades from the 1850s to 1930s have median monthly anomalies below zero (cooler historical climate).\n2. Median anomaly crosses the zero baseline during the 1940s–1950s and rises steadily each subsequent decade.\n3. The 2000s and 2010s show entirely positive anomaly distributions with far fewer cool outliers, proving persistent global heating.\n### Axes Definition\n- X-axis: Decade categorical label (1850s to 2010s)\n- Y-axis: Monthly temperature anomaly relative to 1951–1980 baseline (°C)","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Viz 6: Dual Comparison – Seasonal Absolute Temp vs Monthly Warming Anomaly\n\n# Define 4 representative months for four seasons\nmonths_to_plot = {1: 'January (Winter)', 4: 'April (Spring)', 7: 'July (Summer)', 10: 'October (Autumn)'}\n\n# Filter dataset to records from 1850 onwards\ndf_recent = df[df['Year'] >= 1850].copy()\n\n# Generate 4-color husl palette for seasonal lines\ncolors = sns.color_palette(\"husl\", 4)\n\n# Calculate monthly climate baseline average (1951–1980 reference period)\nmonthly_baseline = df[(df['Year'] >= 1951) & (df['Year'] <= 1980)].groupby('Month')['LandAndOceanAverageTemperature'].mean()\n\n# Compute monthly temperature anomaly vs seasonal baseline\ndf_recent['Monthly_Anomaly'] = df_recent.apply(\n    lambda row: row['LandAndOceanAverageTemperature'] - monthly_baseline.get(row['Month'], np.nan),\n    axis=1\n)\n\n# Create canvas with 1 row, 2 columns of subplots\nfig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(22, 8), dpi=120)\n\n# --------------------------\n# Left Subplot: Raw absolute monthly temperature\n# --------------------------\nfor idx, (month_num, season_label) in enumerate(months_to_plot.items()):\n    # Subset data for single target month\n    monthly_subset = df_recent[df_recent['Month'] == month_num]\n    # 10-year rolling mean smooth raw temperature\n    smoothed_absolute_temp = monthly_subset['LandAndOceanAverageTemperature'].rolling(window=10).mean()\n    ax1.plot(monthly_subset['Year'], smoothed_absolute_temp, label=season_label, color=colors[idx], linewidth=2)\n\nax1.set_title('Seasonal Raw Absolute Temperature (10-Year Rolling Mean)', fontsize=12)\nax1.set_xlabel('Year')\nax1.set_ylabel('Average Absolute Temperature (°C)')\nax1.legend(title='Month/Season')\nax1.grid(alpha=0.3)\n\n# --------------------------\n# Right Subplot: Monthly temperature anomaly (climate standard metric)\n# --------------------------\nfor idx, (month_num, season_label) in enumerate(months_to_plot.items()):\n    monthly_subset = df_recent[df_recent['Month'] == month_num]\n    # 10-year rolling mean smooth temperature anomaly\n    smoothed_anomaly = monthly_subset['Monthly_Anomaly'].rolling(window=10).mean()\n    ax2.plot(monthly_subset['Year'], smoothed_anomaly, label=season_label, color=colors[idx], linewidth=2)\n\nax2.set_title('Seasonal Monthly Temperature Anomaly (10-Year Rolling Mean, 1951–1980 Baseline)', fontsize=12)\nax2.set_xlabel('Year')\nax2.set_ylabel('Temperature Anomaly (°C)')\nax2.legend(title='Month/Season')\nax2.grid(alpha=0.3)\n\n# Global super title and layout adjustment\nfig.suptitle('Warming Trends Across Four Seasons – Absolute Temperature vs Warming Anomaly Comparison', fontsize=15, y=0.98)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-25T04:16:43.119134Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-25T04:16:43.119557Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-25T04:16:43.771379Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-25T04:16:43.119525Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-25T04:16:43.770221Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 2640x960 with 2 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":13},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Two side-by-side subplots with 10-year rolling smoothed monthly temperature data for four representative seasonal months: January (Winter), April (Spring), July (Summer), October (Autumn).\n1. Left Subplot: Raw absolute land-ocean monthly temperature\nDemonstrates inherent permanent seasonal thermal differences; summer naturally holds the highest baseline temperature while winter is the coldest.\n2. Right Subplot: Monthly temperature anomaly (1951–1980 seasonal baseline, standard climate metric)\nEliminates fixed seasonal temperature offsets, unifies all seasons on the same zero reference line to directly compare net warming magnitude across seasons.\n\n### Key Comparative Findings\n1. Natural seasonal temperature stratification (summer > autumn > spring > winter) remains consistent across the full 1860–2015 timeline in absolute temperature view.\n2. Pre-1940 all seasons show negative temperature anomalies, meaning the global climate was persistently cooler relative to the 1951–1980 reference period; winter exhibits the largest cold swings in early industrial eras.\n3. All four seasons cross the zero-anomaly baseline around 1960–1980, followed by a steep synchronized upward warming trend after 1980.\n4. Absolute temperature curves obscure warming magnitude due to fixed seasonal gaps; temperature anomaly provides unbiased comparison of warming rates across all seasons, proving global warming impacts every season uniformly.\n\n### Axes Definition\n- X-axis (both): Calendar Year (1860–2015)\n- Left Y-axis: Absolute average monthly temperature (°C)\n- Right Y-axis: Monthly temperature anomaly relative to 1951–1980 climate baseline (°C)","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Viz 7: Correlation Heatmap (Temperature & Measurement Uncertainty)\n\ncorr_cols = [\n    \"LandAverageTemperature\",\n    \"LandAverageTemperatureUncertainty\",\n    \"LandAndOceanAverageTemperature\",\n    \"LandAndOceanAverageTemperatureUncertainty\"\n]\ncorr_df = df[corr_cols].corr()\nplt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))\nsns.heatmap(\n    corr_df, annot=True, fmt=\".2f\", cmap=\"RdBu_r\", vmin=-1, vmax=1, linewidths=0.5,\n    annot_kws={\"color\": \"white\", \"size\": 10}\n)\nplt.title(\"Correlation Between Temperature and Observation Uncertainty\", fontsize=14)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-25T03:03:03.533698Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-25T03:03:03.534687Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-25T03:03:03.818973Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-25T03:03:03.534654Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-25T03:03:03.818223Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1000x800 with 2 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":8},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Seaborn correlation heatmap for four core variables: land average temperature, land temperature uncertainty, blended land-ocean temperature, blended temperature uncertainty. Cell values = Pearson correlation coefficient (-1 = perfect negative, +1 = perfect positive correlation).\n### Key Findings\n1. Land-only temperature and combined land-ocean temperature have an extremely strong positive correlation (r=0.99), consistent physical linkage of planetary thermal balance.\n2. Temperature measurement uncertainty metrics show strong positive inter-correlation (r=0.97), meaning sparse historical stations increase error uniformly across land and ocean readings.\n3. Weak negative correlations (~-0.2) exist between raw temperature values and their uncertainty: warmer modern decades have far lower measurement error due to global instrument coverage.\n### Axes Definition\n- X/Y axes: Four core temperature & uncertainty variables\n- Color scale: Red = positive correlation, Blue = negative correlation","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Viz 8: Static Scatter Plot of Land Temperature Anomalies (1750–2015)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))\nscatter = plt.scatter(df['Year'], df[\"LandAverageTemperature\"] - df[\"LandAverageTemperature\"].mean(),\n                      c=df[\"LandAverageTemperature\"] - df[\"LandAverageTemperature\"].mean(), cmap=\"RdBu_r\", s=6)\nplt.colorbar(scatter, label=\"Temp_Anomaly (°C)\")\nplt.title(\"Global Land Temperature Anomalies (1750–2015)\", fontsize=14)\nplt.xlabel(\"Year\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Temp_Anomaly (°C)\")\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-25T03:03:15.539676Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-25T03:03:15.540357Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-25T03:03:15.853683Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-25T03:03:15.540325Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-25T03:03:15.85288Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1200x500 with 2 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":9},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Every monthly land temperature measurement plotted as an individual point, colored by its temperature anomaly relative to the full 1750–2015 land temperature mean. Blue points = cool historical months; red points = warm modern months.\n### Key Findings\n1. Pre-1850 data points cluster heavily in blue negative anomaly territory, reflecting pre-industrial cooler global climate.\n2. Point color gradually shifts orange after 1900 and saturates deep red post-1980, with almost no cool blue monthly observations after 2000.\n3. The vertical spread of warm anomalies expands dramatically in recent decades, indicating more frequent extreme warm monthly events.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Viz 9: Interactive Plotly Time Series Charts\n\n# Chart 9.1: Interactive Land vs Land+Ocean Temperature\nfig = px.line(year_df, x=\"Year\", y=[\"LandAverageTemperature\", \"LandAndOceanAverageTemperature\"],\n              labels={\"value\": \"Average Temperature (°C)\", \"variable\": \"Temperature Type\"},\n              title=\"Global Interactive Time Series of Temperature (1850–2015)\")\nfig.update_layout(xaxis_title=\"Year\", yaxis_title=\"Average Temperature (°C)\")\nfig.show()\n\n# Chart 9.2: Interactive Annual Mean + 10-Year Rolling Mean\nfig2 = go.Figure()\nfig2.add_trace(go.Scatter(\n    x=year_df[\"Year\"], y=year_df[\"LandAndOceanAverageTemperature\"],\n    name=\"Annual Average (°C)\", line=dict(color=\"#1f77b4\")\n))\nfig2.add_trace(go.Scatter(\n    x=year_df[\"Year\"], y=year_df[\"Roll10_Mean\"],\n    name=\"10-Year Rolling Mean\", line=dict(dash=\"dash\", color=\"#d62728\")\n))\nfig2.update_layout(\n    title=\"Global Land and Ocean Average Temperature Trend (1750–2015)\",\n    xaxis_title=\"Year\", yaxis_title=\"Average Temperature (°C)\"\n)\nfig2.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-25T03:03:19.283367Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-25T03:03:19.283746Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-25T03:03:22.859808Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-25T03:03:19.283711Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-25T03:03:22.858961Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"<html>\n<head><meta charset=\"utf-8\" /></head>\n<body>\n    <div>            <script src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/mathjax/2.7.5/MathJax.js?config=TeX-AMS-MML_SVG\"></script><script type=\"text/javascript\">if (window.MathJax && window.MathJax.Hub && window.MathJax.Hub.Config) {window.MathJax.Hub.Config({SVG: {font: \"STIX-Web\"}});}</script>                <script type=\"text/javascript\">window.PlotlyConfig = {MathJaxConfig: 'local'};</script>\n        <script charset=\"utf-8\" src=\"https://cdn.plot.ly/plotly-2.35.2.min.js\"></script>                <div id=\"e1461990-641a-4adf-a3f3-b03310e8d5d1\" class=\"plotly-graph-div\" style=\"height:525px; width:100%;\"></div>            <script type=\"text/javascript\">                                    window.PLOTLYENV=window.PLOTLYENV || {};                                    if (document.getElementById(\"e1461990-641a-4adf-a3f3-b03310e8d5d1\")) {                    Plotly.newPlot(                        \"e1461990-641a-4adf-a3f3-b03310e8d5d1\",                        [{\"hovertemplate\":\"Temperature Type=LandAverageTemperature\\u003cbr\\u003eYear=%{x}\\u003cbr\\u003eAverage Temperature (°C)=%{y}\\u003cextra\\u003e\\u003c\\u002fextra\\u003e\",\"legendgroup\":\"LandAverageTemperatur