ming (1990–2015).","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Research Use Case\nEnables granular exploration of short-term climate oscillations superimposed on the long warming trend, ideal for interactive reader exploration.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Overall Research Conclusions\n1. The full dataset (1750–2015) delivers unambiguous statistical evidence of consistent global surface warming, with accelerated heating post-1950 matching IPCC anthropogenic climate change projections.\n2. Continental land surfaces warm faster than ocean-integrated global temperatures, and nighttime minimum temperatures rise more rapidly than daytime maximums, compressing global diurnal temperature ranges.\n3. All four seasonal cycles exhibit upward warming trends, with summer experiencing the strongest total temperature increase over the study period.\n4. Decadal temperature anomaly distributions shift uniformly from cool-negative to warm-positive values across the 165-year instrumental record.\n5. Historical measurement uncertainty declines sharply after mid-20th century due to global weather station network expansion, eliminating data quality concerns for modern warming signals.\n6. Interactive Plotly visualizations allow readers to independently verify short-term climate variability while isolating the irreversible multi-century warming trend.\n\n## Dataset Citation\nBerkeley Earth. (2025). Climate Change: Earth Surface Temperature Data. Kaggle. https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/berkeleyearth/climate-change-earth-surface-temperature-data\n## Dependencies\nPython 3.9+, pandas, numpy, matplotlib, seaborn, scipy, scikit-learn, plotly","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":true}}]}